See also the Facebook page: „Matisyahu Music against the Love of God”. Matti Friedman in the Washington Post writes: “The song was written by a religiously observant man. While modern listeners are comfortable with sexual ambiguity, a man who "comes out of the woods" while uninhibited about his sexuality was likely to be something much more old-fashioned in ancient Israel. He might be, say, a warlock — a pagan wizard who made deals with demons. And some said that the best way to keep a wizard under control was to catch him, lock him up and stone him, for the protection of society. So Matthew 5:21-22, the warning to scribes not to call any man "a fool" lest Heaven take the same approach, might be interpreted as a signal from Jesus not to call these Judean radicals "magicians", that is, Warlocks.
